04826nam a22006855i 9780226547688DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802265476887 a10.7208/97802265476882doi  a(DE-B1597)523418  a(OCoLC)1028979754  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQH541.15.R45bH38 2018eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a333.73/1532231 aHavlick, David G., eauthor.10aBombs Away :bMilitarization, Conservation, and Ecological Restoration /cDavid G. Havlick. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (208 p.) :b36 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tOne. Military Natures -- tTwo. Bunkers, Bats, and Base Closures -- tThree. Real Restoration? -- tFour. Sanctuaries Inviolate -- tFive. Not Nature Alone -- tSix. Army Green -- tSeven. Remembering and Restoring Militarized Landscapes -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhen viewed from space, the Korean Peninsula is crossed by a thin green ribbon. On the ground, its mix of dense vegetation and cleared borderlands serves as home to dozens of species that are extinct or endangered elsewhere on the peninsula. This is Korea's demilitarized zone-one of the most dangerous places on earth for humans, and paradoxically one of the safest for wildlife. Although this zone was not intentionally created for conservation, across the globe hundreds of millions of acres of former military zones and bases are being converted to restoration areas, refuges, and conservation lands. David G. Havlick has traveled the world visiting these spaces of military-to-wildlife transition, and in Bombs Away he explores both the challenges-physical, historical, and cultural-and fascinating ecological possibilities of military site conversions. Looking at particular international sites of transition-from Indiana's Big Oaks National Wildlife Refuge to Cold War remnants along the former Iron Curtain-Havlick argues that these new frontiers of conservation must accomplish seemingly antithetical aims: rebuilding and protecting ecosystems, or restoring life, while also commemorating the historical and cultural legacies of warfare and militarization. Developing these ideas further, he shows that despite the ecological devastation often wrought by military testing and training, these activities need not be inconsistent with environmental goals, and in some cases can even complement them-a concept he calls ecological militarization. A profound, clear explication of landscapes both fraught and fecund, marked by death but also reservoirs of life, Bombs Away shows us how "military activities, conservation goals, and ecological restoration efforts are made to work together to create new kinds of places and new conceptions of place."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aMilitary base conversionzUnited States. 0aMilitary base conversion. 0aNature conservationzUnited States. 0aNature conservation. 0aRestoration ecologyzUnited States. 0aRestoration ecology. 4aIron Curtain. 4aconservation. 4ademilitarized zone. 4aecological restoration. 4aenvironmental protection. 4ahistorical erasure. 4amilitarization. 4amilitarized landscapes. 4awildlife refuges. 70(DE-601)10575272X0(DE-588)4123769-9aMilitärische Anlage2gnd 70(DE-601)1058150550(DE-588)4115348-0aNaturschutz2gnd 70(DE-601)2407117770(DE-588)4489421-1aFolgenutzung2gnd 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226547688423Coveruhttps://w